 ENDF/B-VI MOD 4 Evaluation, October 1997, S. Chiba,              2437 1451
                 M.B. Chadwick, and P.G. Young (LANL)             2437 1451
                                                                  2437 1451
 Los Alamos LA150 Library, produced with FKK/GNASH/GSCAN code     2437 1451
   in cooperation with ECN Petten.                                2437 1451
                                                                  2437 1451
  This evaluation provides a complete representation of the       2437 1451
nuclear data needed for transport, damage, heating,               2437 1451
radioactivity, and shielding applications over the incident       2437 1451
neutron energy range from 1.0E-11 to 150 MeV.  The discussion     2437 1451
here is divided into the region below and above 20 MeV.           2437 1451
                                                                  2437 1451
INCIDENT NEUTRON ENERGIES < 20 MeV                                2437 1451
                                                                  2437 1451
  Below 20 MeV the evaluation is based completely on the ENDF/B-  2437 1451
VI.5 (Release 2) evaluation by D. Hetrick, D. Larson, N. Larson,  2437 1451
and C. Y. Fu.                                                     2437 1451
                                                                  2437 1451
INCIDENT NEUTRON ENERGIES > 20 MeV                                2437 1451
                                                                  2437 1451
  The ENDF/B-VI Release 2 evaluation extends to 20 MeV and        2437 1451
includes cross sections and energy-angle data for all             2437 1451
significant reactions.  The present evaluation utilizes a more    2437 1451
compact composite reaction spectrum representation above 20 MeV   2437 1451
in order to reduce the length of the file. No essential data for  2437 1451
applications is lost with this representation.                    2437 1451
  The evaluation above 20 MeV utilizes MF=6, MT=5 to represent    2437 1451
all reaction data.  Production cross sections and emission        2437 1451
spectra are given for neutrons, protons, deuterons, tritons,      2437 1451
alpha particles, gamma rays, and all residual nuclides produced   2437 1451
(A>5) in the reaction chains. To summarize, the ENDF sections     2437 1451
with non-zero data above En = 20 MeV are:                         2437 1451
                                                                  2437 1451
  MF=3 MT=  1  Total Cross Section                                2437 1451
       MT=  2  Elastic Scattering Cross Section                   2437 1451
       MT=  3  Nonelastic Cross Section                           2437 1451
       MT=  5  Sum of Binary (n,n') and (n,x) Reactions           2437 1451
                                                                  2437 1451
  MF=4 MT=  2  Elastic Angular Distributions                      2437 1451
                                                                  2437 1451
  MF=6 MT=  5  Production Cross Sections and Energy-Angle         2437 1451
               Distributions for Emission Neutrons, Protons,      2437 1451
               Deuterons, Tritons, and Alphas; and Angle-         2437 1451
               Integrated Spectra for Gamma Rays and Residual     2437 1451
               Nuclei That Are Stable Against Particle Emission   2437 1451
                                                                  2437 1451
  The evaluation is based on nuclear model calculations that      2437 1451
have been benchmarked to experimental data, especially for n +    2437 1451
Cr52 and p + Cr52 reactions [Ch97]. We use the GNASH code system  2437 1451
[Yo92], which utilizes Hauser-Feshbach statistical,               2437 1451
preequilibrium and direct-reaction theories. Spherical optical    2437 1451
model calculations are used to obtain particle transmission       2437 1451
coefficients for the Hauser-Feshbach calculations, as well as     2437 1451
for the elastic neutron angular distributions.                    2437 1451
  Cross sections and spectra for producing individual residual    2437 1451
nuclei are included for reactions. The energy-angle-correlations  2437 1451
for all outgoing particles are based on Kalbach systematics       2437 1451
[Ka88].                                                           2437 1451
  A model was developed to calculate the energy distributions of  2437 1451
all recoil nuclei in the GNASH calculations [Ch96]. The recoil    2437 1451
energy distributions are represented in the laboratory system in  2437 1451
MT=5, MF=6, and are given as isotropic in the lab system. All     2437 1451
other data in MT=5,MF=6 are given in the center-of-mass system.   2437 1451
This method of representation utilizes the LCT=3 option approved  2437 1451
at the November, 1996, CSEWG meeting.                             2437 1451
  Preequilibrium corrections were performed in the course of the  2437 1451
GNASH calculations using the exciton model of Kalbach [Ka77,      2437 1451
Ka85], validated by comparison with calculations using Feshbach,  2437 1451
Kerman, Koonin (FKK) theory [Ch93].  Discrete level data from     2437 1451
nuclear data sheets were matched to continuum level densities     2437 1451
using the formulation of Ignatyuk et al. [Ig75] and pairing and   2437 1451
shell parameters from the Cook [Co67] analysis. Neutron and       2437 1451
charged- particle transmission coefficients were obtained from    2437 1451
the optical potentials, as discussed below.  Gamma-ray            2437 1451
transmission coefficients were calculated using the Kopecky-Uhl   2437 1451
model [Ko90].                                                     2437 1451
                                                                  2437 1451
SOME Cr-SPECIFIC INFORMATION CONCERNING THE EVAL.                 2437 1451
                                                                  2437 1451
  The neutron total cross section was evaluated at energy grid    2437 1451
points by using the least-squares code GMA [Po81] taking account  2437 1451
of the new data measured by Dietrich et al. for natural Cr[Di97]. 2437 1451
The results were transformed to the Cr-54 cross section according 2437 1451
to the A*(2/3) law, i.e., by multiplying by a factor of 1.024767. 2437 1451
                                                                  2437 1451
  The neutron optical model potential derived for n + Cr-52 was   2437 1451
used for calculation of DWBA cross sections.                      2437 1451
                                                                  2437 1451
  The transmission coefficients calculated for the n + Cr-52      2437 1451
evaluation were employed for all the n + Cr-54 evaluation         2437 1451
channels, by multiplying by a factor of 1.025479, i.e., a ratio of2437 1451
A**(2/3) between Cr-54 and Cr-52.                                 2437 1451
                                                                  2437 1451
  The Cr-52 transmission coefficients were calculated by using the2437 1451
following potentials:                                             2437 1451
                                                                  2437 1451
  For the neutron channel, the newly-searched potential for n +   2437 1451
Cr-52, as described in File 1 of the n + Cr-52 evaluation, was    2437 1451
used.                                                             2437 1451
                                                                  2437 1451
  For the proton channel, a combination of 2 potentials was used :2437 1451
                                                                  2437 1451
below 40 MeV : Becchetti-Greenlees [Be69]                         2437 1451
above 40 MeV : Madland medium energy potential [Ma88]             2437 1451
                                                                  2437 1451
  The proton reaction cross section and transmission coefficients 2437 1451
below 40 MeV were multiplied by a factor of 0.845 to make the     2437 1451
agreement with the measured proton reaction cross section [Ca96]  2437 1451
better, and also to make the connection to higher energy values   2437 1451
smoothly.                                                         2437 1451
                                                                  2437 1451
  For deuterons, the Lohr-Haeberli [Lo74] global potential was    2437 1451
used; for alpha particles the McFadden-Satchler [Mc66] potential  2437 1451
was used; and for tritons the Becchetti-Greenlees [Be71] potential2437 1451
was used.  The He-3 channel was ignored.                          2437 1451
                                                                  2437 1451
  The direct collective inelastic scattering to the following     2437 1451
levels in Cr-54 was considered by the DWBA-mode calculation of    2437 1451
ECIS95:                                                           2437 1451
